## How the MCP server works

- **Wiring**: `tenex-edge mcp` (`src/cli/mcp.rs:50`) runs a stdio JSON-RPC loop by default (`stdio()`, `src/cli/mcp.rs:57-91`) â€” this is spawned as a per-session subprocess by the harness (e.g. Claude Code). It's stateless itself.
- **Real state lives elsewhere**: every tool call is forwarded over a Unix domain socket to a separate, long-running per-machine daemon (`src/daemon/client.rs`), which auto-spawns if not already running. So the MCP process is just an RPC translator; sessions/channels/roster all live in the daemon.
- **Tools**: `who`, `channels_list`, `chat_read`, `chat_write`, `channels_create`, `channels_join/leave/switch` (`src/cli/mcp/catalog.rs:29-109`).

## The `who` tool and identity resolution

`who` (`src/cli/mcp/tools.rs:32-48`) sends caller-identity fields â€” `pty_session`, `harness`/`watch_pid`, `agent`, `group`, `cwd` â€” all read from **environment variables**, not a config file (`src/cli/context.rs:15-47`). The daemon-side handler `rpc_who` (`src/daemon/server/who.rs:39-84`) uses these to resolve a live `Session` via `CallerAnchor` resolution.

## What happens with no agent context (your question)

If the MCP server is started with **zero** session context (no PTY session env, no harness id, no watch-pid, no agent/group env â€” e.g. launched standalone outside any tenex-edge session):

```rust
let caller_rec = if p.all_roots {
    None
} else if p.pty_session.is_some() || p.harness_session.is_some() || p.watch_pid.is_some() {
    Some(resolve_session_inner(state, &anchor, ResolveScope::Strict)?)
} else if p.agent.is_some() || p.group.is_some() {
    anyhow::bail!("who needs an exact live session anchor; agent/channel env alone is not session context");
} else {
    None   // <-- fully standalone: no error
};
```

It **doesn't crash or error** â€” it silently falls into `caller_rec = None`. From there:

- `current_root` falls back to `workspace::resolve(cwd)`, which is `.unwrap_or_default()`-collapsed to `""` if not in a git repo.
- `self_slug`/`self_pubkey` also default to `""` (`.unwrap_or_default()`).
- In the fabric render (`src/fabric_context/build.rs`), `self_row` is simply **omitted** (not shown as "unknown" or any placeholder) since `input.session` is `None`.
- Since no real roster member has an empty pubkey, nothing ever matches `self_pubkey`, so the caller never gets tagged `(you)` in the member list.
- If cwd isn't inside a known channel, a warning is added instead: `"Fabric channel "" is unavailable: no relay-backed channel metadata exists locally..."`.

**Bottom line**: it degrades gracefully rather than showing a sentinel value â€” you get an anonymous, session-less fabric snapshot with no self-row and no `(you)` marker, plus possible availability warnings. The only *hard* failures are when a **stale/dead** anchor is explicitly supplied (PTY/harness/watch-pid resolves to nothing â†’ `Strict` scope bails with "must be run from within a tenex-edge agent session...") or when `agent`/`group` env is set alone without a resolvable session (explicit bail: "who needs an exact live session anchor; agent/channel env alone is not session context").
